EM using mclust

# 1. Importing data
data1 = read.csv(file ="data1.csv",header=T)
data2 = read.csv(file="data2.csv",header=T)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
col1 = data1$truth
X1=data1$X1
X2=data1$X2
plot(X1,X2,col=col1,main="Data1")
col2 = data2$truth
X1=data2$X1
X2=data2$X2
plot(X1,X2,col=col2,main="Data2")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

# 2. Applying k-means on both datasets
km1=kmeans(data1,centers = 4,iter.max = 20)
km2=kmeans(data2,centers = 4,iter.max = 20)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(data1$X1,data1$X2,col=km1$cluster,pch=20,cex=1)
points(km1$centers,col=1:4,pch=3,cex=3,lwd=3)

plot(data2$X1,data2$X2,col=km2$cluster,pch=20,cex=1)
points(km2$centers,col=1:4,pch=3,cex=3,lwd=3)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

# We can see that k-means is not very accurate for the second dataset.

# 3. Loading the library and applying Mclust() function

library('mclust')
## Warning: package 'mclust' was built under R version 3.6.3
## Package 'mclust' version 5.4.7
## Type 'citation("mclust")' for citing this R package in publications.
data=data2[,1:2]
gmm2=Mclust(data)
plot(gmm2$data,col=gmm2$classification)

# We can see that this method is way better than kmeans for this type of dataset.

# 4. Showing the summary of the GMM model

summary(gmm2)
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## Gaussian finite mixture model fitted by EM algorithm 
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## 
## Mclust EEE (ellipsoidal, equal volume, shape and orientation) model with 4
## components: 
## 
##  log-likelihood   n df       BIC       ICL
##       -938.8639 400 14 -1961.608 -1965.709
## 
## Clustering table:
##   1   2   3   4 
## 100  99 101 100
# The function is showing us that the best model is EEE with 4 components. It also shows the number of observations in each cluster.

# 5. Plotting the data

plot(gmm2, what = "classification")

# This plot shows the ellipsoids and their radius. They are also colorated depending on their cluster.

plot(gmm2, what = "uncertainty")

# This plot shows the level of uncertainty of each observation in addition of all the features of the previous plot.

# 6. Plotting BIC in function of number of mixtures

plot(gmm2, what = "BIC")

# We can see that the best BIC value is around 2000 and that EEE with 4 components is the best model.

# 7. Applying density estimate on GMM

plot(densityMclust(data),what="density",type="persp")

plot(densityMclust(data),what="density",type="image")

## EM on 1D

# 8. Create the data table

set.seed(709387)
r1=rnorm(100,mean=5,sd=1.5)
r2=rnorm(100,mean=0,sd=2)
r3=rnorm(100,mean=-5,sd=0.5)
X=c(r1,r2,r3)
c1=rep(1,100)
c2=rep(2,100)
c3=rep(3,100)
source=c(c1,c2,c3)
data=data.frame(X,source)

# 9. Showing the data

stripchart(data$X,col = data$source, bg=data$source,pch=21)

# 10. Plotting the histogram

hist(data$X)

# We can see that, we have a gaussian distribution and the means are -5, 0 and 5.

# 11. Fitting a GMM model

gmm = Mclust(data$X)

summary(gmm)
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## Gaussian finite mixture model fitted by EM algorithm 
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## 
## Mclust V (univariate, unequal variance) model with 3 components: 
## 
##  log-likelihood   n df       BIC       ICL
##       -750.6743 300  8 -1546.979 -1583.211
## 
## Clustering table:
##   1   2   3 
## 103  93 104
plot(gmm, what="classification")

# Some observations are overlapped, so difficult to predict. That's why the summary doesn't show 100-100-100 but 103-93-104.

# 12. Applying the desity estimate on the data

plot(densityMclust(data$X),what="density")

# We can see 3 peaks : one at -5, one at 0 and one at 5. These are the means and we can see that the height is high when the standard deviation is low and vice versa.

# 2.1 Generating a two-dimensional dataset from a k-component Gaussian mixture density.

r1=rnorm(100,mean=5,sd=1.5)
r2=rnorm(100,mean=0,sd=2)
r3=rnorm(100,mean=-5,sd=1)
X1=c(r1,r2,r3)
r1=rnorm(100,mean=8,sd=1.5)
r2=rnorm(100,mean=2,sd=2)
r3=rnorm(100,mean=-4,sd=1)
X2=c(r1,r2,r3)
c1=rep(1,100)
c2=rep(2,100)
c3=rep(3,100)
source=c(c1,c2,c3)
data=data.frame(X1,X2,source)
plot(data$X1,data$X2,col=data$source)
